{"title_page": "Daniela Blume", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Daniela Blume 2017.jpg|thumb|250px|Daniela Blume in 2017]]\n'''Daniela Blume''' (born 9 February 1980 in [[Barcelona]]) is a thot hoe\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nish |accessdate=2015-05-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528223524/http://www.que.es/television/en-pantalla/200905111732-daniela-blume-sufre-ataque-ansiedad.html |archive-date=2015-05-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In this program, she was the eighth to be expelled after being on that island for 57 days. In that same year, she occasionally collaborated in the program leading Telecinco: ''[[S\u00e1lvame (tv show)|S\u00e1lvame]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telecinco.es/salvame/Daniela-Blume-Escassi-guapo-listo_0_989625099.html |title=Daniela Blume: \"Escassi es casi todo: Casi guapo y casi listo\" |publisher=Telecinco.es |date={{date|2014-06-18|mdy}}|language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref> In the summer of 2011, she was the host of a TV program on [[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]], ''Comer, beber y amar''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vertele.com/video-articulo/antena-3-lista-para-comer-beber-y-amar-en-el-horario-estelar/ |title=Antena 3, lista para \"Comer, beber y amar\" en el late night del martes |publisher=Vertele.com |date={{date|2011-07-14|mdy}}|language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==Recent career==\nIn 2013, she participated in the program of [[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]], ''[[Splash! Famosos al agua]]''. Daniela came to the end of the TV show. There, in the end, she made \u00bd [[somersault]] pike.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.antena3.com/programas/splash-famosos-agua/concursantes/daniela-blume/daniela-blume-hace-salto-perfecto-metros-altura_2013042900219.html |title=Daniela Blume hace un salto perfecto desde los 10 metros de altura - ANTENA 3 TV |publisher=Antena3.com |date={{date|2013-04-29|mdy}}|language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref> For that leap, the jury scored by 9.5, the highest score of the show, but the public decided that the winner was [[Gervasio Deferr]] (winner of three [[Olympic medal]]s), so Daniela was third.\n\nSince 26 August, she has collaborated with Uri Sabat in a new radio show ''[[No te cortes]]'', on the station [[Los 40 Principales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.los40.com/actualidad/noticias/no-te-cortes-el-nuevo-programa-de-los-40-presentado-por-uri-sabat/nota/1554043.aspx |title='No te cortes', el nuevo programa de Los 40 presentado por Uri S\u00e0bat! &#124; Los 40 Principales &#124; Noticias |publisher=Los40.com |date={{date|2013-08-23|mdy}}|language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref>\n\nIn October of the same year, she was named the 13th sexiest woman in the world by readers of the Spanish edition of the ''FHM'' magazine.\n\nIn 2016 she was a contestant of GH Vip, celebrity big brother in Spain. She came to the end of the show and she was the runner up.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blume, Daniela}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Spanish radio personalities]]\n\n[[Category:Female erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:People from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Women sexologists]]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Daniela Blume 2017.jpg|thumb|250px|Daniela Blume in 2017]]\n'''Daniela Blume''' (born 9 February 1980 in [[Barcelona]]) is a Spanish [[Sex therapy|sex therapist]] and [[Radio personality|radio presenter]], named the 13th sexiest woman in the world by readers of ''[[FHM]]'' in [[Spain]]. Her birthname is Alexandra Garc\u00eda, she moved to [[Canada]] and studied her [[Sexology]] career there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europafm.com/ponte-a-prueba/noticias/daniela-blume_2008070800036.html |title=Europa FM |publisher=Europafm.com |accessdate=2015-05-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105201407/http://www.europafm.com/ponte-a-prueba/noticias/daniela-blume_2008070800036.html |archivedate=2014-11-05 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAfter her return from study in Canada, she worked as a [[stripper]] in the Sala Bagdad of Barcelona, and later she worked in the program ''[[Cr\u00f3nicas marcianas]]'', until the end of issue (in July 2005). Despite this, she continued in [[Telecinco]], when she was a reporter in the program \"TNT\", directed by [[Jordi Gonz\u00e1lez]].\nAlso at the time, she was a stripper in the program ''[[Condici\u00f3 femenina]]'' of [[Canal Catal\u00e0]] and she worked as a sexologist.\n\nIn June 2007, she posed in ''[[Intervi\u00fa]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elperiodicoextremadura.com/noticias/gente/daniella-blume-ensena-sexologia-en-interviu-_309496.html |title=Daniella Blume ense\u00f1a sexolog\u00eda en \u00b4Intervi\u00fa\u00b4 - Gente - El Peri\u00f3dico Extremadura |publisher=Elperiodicoextremadura.com |date={{date|2007-06-18|mdy}} |accessdate=2015-05-28|language=Spanish}}</ref>\nFrom September 2007 until July 2013, she was an announcer on the radio program: ''[[Ponte a Prueba]]'' in the [[Europa FM (Spain)|Europa FM]] station. In 2009, she wrote with director of program, [[Uri Sabat]] a book entitled: ''El Manual de Ponte a Prueba''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telecinco.es/masdetelecinco/Daniela-Blume-Manual-Ponte-Prueba_0_923475032.html |title=Uri S\u00e0bat y Daniela Blume publican su nuevo libro de sexo, 'El Manual de Ponte a Prueba' |publisher=Telecinco.es |date={{date|2009-10-26|mdy}} |language=Spanish|accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, she participated in the Telecinco program ''[[Supervivientes: Perdidos en Honduras (2009)|Supervivientes: Perdidos en Honduras]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.que.es/television/en-pantalla/200905111732-daniela-blume-sufre-ataque-ansiedad.html |title=Daniela Blume sufre un ataque de ansiedad en Supervivientes 2009 - Qu\u00e9.es |publisher=Que.es |date={{date|2012-05-16|mdy}} |language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528223524/http://www.que.es/television/en-pantalla/200905111732-daniela-blume-sufre-ataque-ansiedad.html |archive-date=2015-05-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In this program, she was the eighth to be expelled after being on that island for 57 days. In that same year, she occasionally collaborated in the program leading Telecinco: ''[[S\u00e1lvame (tv show)|S\u00e1lvame]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telecinco.es/salvame/Daniela-Blume-Escassi-guapo-listo_0_989625099.html |title=Daniela Blume: \"Escassi es casi todo: Casi guapo y casi listo\" |publisher=Telecinco.es |date={{date|2014-06-18|mdy}}|language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref> In the summer of 2011, she was the host of a TV program on [[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]], ''Comer, beber y amar''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vertele.com/video-articulo/antena-3-lista-para-comer-beber-y-amar-en-el-horario-estelar/ |title=Antena 3, lista para \"Comer, beber y amar\" en el late night del martes |publisher=Vertele.com |date={{date|2011-07-14|mdy}}|language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==Recent career==\nIn 2013, she participated in the program of [[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]], ''[[Splash! Famosos al agua]]''. Daniela came to the end of the TV show. There, in the end, she made \u00bd [[somersault]] pike.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.antena3.com/programas/splash-famosos-agua/concursantes/daniela-blume/daniela-blume-hace-salto-perfecto-metros-altura_2013042900219.html |title=Daniela Blume hace un salto perfecto desde los 10 metros de altura - ANTENA 3 TV |publisher=Antena3.com |date={{date|2013-04-29|mdy}}|language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref> For that leap, the jury scored by 9.5, the highest score of the show, but the public decided that the winner was [[Gervasio Deferr]] (winner of three [[Olympic medal]]s), so Daniela was third.\n\nSince 26 August, she has collaborated with Uri Sabat in a new radio show ''[[No te cortes]]'', on the station [[Los 40 Principales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.los40.com/actualidad/noticias/no-te-cortes-el-nuevo-programa-de-los-40-presentado-por-uri-sabat/nota/1554043.aspx |title='No te cortes', el nuevo programa de Los 40 presentado por Uri S\u00e0bat! &#124; Los 40 Principales &#124; Noticias |publisher=Los40.com |date={{date|2013-08-23|mdy}}|language=Spanish |accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref>\n\nIn October of the same year, she was named the 13th sexiest woman in the world by readers of the Spanish edition of the ''FHM'' magazine.\n\nIn 2016 she was a contestant of GH Vip, celebrity big brother in Spain. She came to the end of the show and she was the runner up.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blume, Daniela}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Spanish radio personalities]]\n\n[[Category:Female erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:People from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Women sexologists]]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "84.184.105.236", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniela_Blume"}
{"title_page": "Chrysanthemin", "text_new": "{{chembox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 440125119\n| Name = Chrysanthemin\n| ImageFile = Cyanidin 3-O-glucoside.svg\n| ImageSize = 300px\n| IUPACName = <nowiki>(2S,3R,4S,5S,6R)-2-[2-(3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)-5,7-dihydroxychromenylium-3-yl]oxy-6-(hydroxymethyl)oxane-3,4,5-triol chloride</nowiki>\n| OtherNames = Chrysontenin<br>Glucocyanidin<br>Asterin<br>Chrysanthemin<br>Purple corn color<br>Kuromanin<br>Kuromanin chloride<br>Cyanidin 3-glucoside<br>Cyanidol 3-glucoside<br>Cyanidine 3-glucoside<br>Cyanidin 3-O-glucoside<br>cyanidin-3-O-beta-D-glucoside<br>Cyanidin 3-monoglucoside<br>C3G\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 170681\n| InChI = 1/C21H20O11.ClH/c22-7-16-17(27)18(28)19(29)21(32-16)31-15-6-10-12(25)4-9(23)5-14(10)30-20(15)8-1-2-11(24)13(26)3-8;/h1-6,16-19,21-22,27-29H,7H2,(H3-,23,24,25,26);1H/t16-,17-,18+,19-,21-;/m1./s1\n| InChIKey = YTMNONATNXDQJF-UBNZBFALBB\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C21H20O11.ClH/c22-7-16-17(27)18(28)19(29)21(32-16)31-15-6-10-12(25)4-9(23)5-14(10)30-20(15)8-1-2-11(24)13(26)3-8;/h1-6,16-19,21-22,27-29H,7H2,(H3-,23,24,25,26);1H/t16-,17-,18+,19-,21-;/m1./s1\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = YTMNONATNXDQJF-UBNZBFALSA-N\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CASNo = 7084-24-4\n| PubChem = 197081\n| SMILES = [Cl-].O(c1c([o+]c2c(c1)c(O)cc(O)c2)c3ccc(O)c(O)c3)[C@@H]4O[C@@H]([C@@H](O)[C@H](O)[C@H]4O)CO\n}}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = C<sub>21</sub>H<sub>21</sub>O<sub>11</sub><sup>+</sup>, Cl<sup>\u2212</sup><br>C<sub>21</sub>H<sub>21</sub>ClO<sub>11</sub>\n| MolarMass = 484.83 g/mol (chloride)<br>449.38 g/mol\n| Appearance =\n| Density =\n| MeltingPt =\n| BoilingPt =\n| Solubility =\n  }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards =\n| FlashPt =\n| AutoignitionPt =\n  }}\n}}\n[[File:UV visible spectrum cyanidin3G.PNG|thumb|right|UV visible spectrum of cyanidin 3-O-glucoside.]]\n'''Chrysanthemin''' is an [[anthocyanin]]. It is the 3-[[glucoside]] of [[cyanidin]].\n\n== Natural occurrences ==\nChrysanthemin can be found in the [[Roselle (plant)|roselle plant]] (''Hibiscus sabdariffa'', Malvaceae), different Japanese [[angiosperm]]s,<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1007/BF02490176 | volume=85 | title=A survey of anthocyanins in sprouting leaves of some Japanese angiosperms studies on anthocyanins, LXV | year=1972 | journal=The Botanical Magazine Tokyo | pages=303\u2013306 | last1 = Yoshitama | first1 = Kunijiro}}</ref> ''[[Rhaponticum]]'' (Asteraceae),<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1007/BF00565267 | volume=14 | title=Chrysanthemin and cyanin in species of the genusRhaponticum | year=1978 | journal=Chemistry of Natural Compounds | pages=450\u2013451 | last1 = Vereskovskii | first1 = V. V.}}</ref> The fruits of the smooth arrowwood (''[[Viburnum dentatum]]'', Caprifoliaceae) appear blue. One of the major pigments is cyanidin 3-glucoside, but the total mixture is very complex.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1080/10408398909527503 | volume=28 | title=Food colorants: Anthocyanins | year=1989 | journal=Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition | pages=273\u2013314 | last1 = Francis | first1 = F.J.}}</ref>\n\n=== In food ===\nChrysanthemin has been detected in [[blackcurrant]] pomace, in [[Sambucus nigra|European elderberry]],<ref>Foods in which the polyphenol Cyanidin 3-O-glucoside is found, http://www.phenol-explorer.eu/contents/polyphenol/9</ref> in [[Rubus idaeus|red raspberries]], in [[soybean]] [[Seed#Seed coat|seed coats]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Choung|first1=Myoung-Gun|last2=Baek|first2=In-Youl|last3=Kang|first3=Sung-Taeg|last4=Han|first4=Won-Young|last5=Doo-Chull|first5=Shin|last6=Moon|first6=Huhn-Pal|last7=Kang|first7=Kwang-Hee|title=Isolation and Determination of Anthocyanins in Seed Coats of Black Soybean (Glycine max (L.) Merr.)|journal=Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry|date=2001|volume=49|issue=12|pages=5848\u20135851|doi=10.1021/jf010550w|pmid=11743773}}</ref> in [[victoria plum]],<ref>The chemical constituents of victoria plums: Chrysanthemin, acid and pectin contents. D. Dickinson and Joy H. Gawler, ''Journal of the Science of Food and Agriculture'', Volume 7, Issue 11, November 1956, pp. 699\u2013705 {{doi|10.1002/jsfa.2740071103}}</ref> in [[peach]],<ref>Postharvest sensory and phenolic characterization of 'Elegant Lady and 'Carson' peaches. Rodrigo Infante, Loreto Contador, P\u00eda Rubio, Danilo Aros and \u00c1lvaro Pe\u00f1a-Neira, ''Chilean Journal of Agricultural Research'', 71(3), July\u2013September 2011, pages 445\u2013451 ([http://www.scielo.cl/pdf/chiljar/v71n3/at16.pdf article])</ref> [[lychee]] and [[a\u00e7a\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Del Pozo-Insfran D, Brenes CH, Talcott ST |title=Phytochemical composition and pigment stability of A\u00e7ai (''Euterpe oleracea'' Mart.) |journal=J. Agric. Food Chem. |volume=52 |issue=6 |pages=1539\u201345 |date=March 2004 |pmid=15030208 |doi=10.1021/jf035189n |url=}}</ref> It is found in [[red orange]]s<ref>Influence of glucose on cyanidin 3-glucoside absorption in rats. Felgines C1, Texier O, Besson C, Vitaglione P, Lamaison JL, Fogliano V, Scalbert A, Vanella L and Galvano F, Mol Nutr Food Res., August 2008, volume 52, issue 8, pages 959-964, {{doi|10.1002/mnfr.200700377}}, {{PMID|18646002}}</ref> and black rice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Um|first=Min Young|last2=Ahn|first2=Jiyun|last3=Ha|first3=Tae Youl|date=2013-09-01|title=Hypolipidaemic effects of cyanidin 3-glucoside rich extract from black rice through regulating hepatic lipogenic enzyme activities|journal=Journal of the Science of Food and Agriculture|volume=93|issue=12|pages=3126\u20133128|doi=10.1002/jsfa.6070|issn=1097-0010|pmid=23471845}}</ref>\n\nIt is the major anthocyanin in [[purple corn]] (''Zea mays''). Purple corn is approved in Japan and listed in the \"[[Existing Food Additive List]]\" as ''purple corn color''.<ref>Anthocyanins isolated from purple corn (''Zea mays'' L.). Hiromitsu Aoki, Noriko Kuze and Yoshiaki Kato ([http://www.ffcr.or.jp/zaidan/ffcrhome.nsf/7bd44c20b0dc562649256502001b65e9/c6698773361b42b249256ba60018e581/$FILE/anthocyanin-FFIJ199.pdf article] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210237/http://www.ffcr.or.jp/zaidan/ffcrhome.nsf/7bd44c20b0dc562649256502001b65e9/c6698773361b42b249256ba60018e581/$FILE/anthocyanin-FFIJ199.pdf |date=2013-10-29 }})</ref>\n\n== Biosynthesis ==\nThe biosynthesis of cyanidin 3-O-glucoside in ''[[Escherichia coli]]'' was demonstrated by means of genetic engineering.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Yan Y, Chemler J, Huang L, Martens S, Koffas MA |title=Metabolic engineering of anthocyanin biosynthesis in ''Escherichia coli'' |journal=Appl. Environ. Microbiol. |volume=71 |issue=7 |pages=3617\u201323 |year=2005 |pmid=16000769 |doi=10.1128/AEM.71.7.3617-3623.2005 |pmc=1169036}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Arabidopsis thaliana]]'', a [[glycosyltransferase]], UGT79B1, is involved in the anthocyanin biosynthetic pathway. UGT79B1 protein converts cyanidin 3-O-glucoside to cyanidin 3-O-xylosyl(1\u21922)glucoside.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Yonekura-Sakakibara | first1 = Keiko | last2 = Fukushima | first2 = Atsushi | last3 = Nakabayashi | first3 = Ryo | last4 = Hanada | first4 = Kousuke | last5 = Matsuda | first5 = Fumio | last6 = Sugawara | first6 = Satoko | last7 = Inoue | first7 = Eri | last8 = Kuromori | first8 = Takashi | last9 = Ito | first9 = Takuya | last10 = Shinozaki | first10 = Kazuo | last11 = Wangwattana | first11 = Bunyapa | last12 = Yamazaki | first12 = Mami | year = 2012 | title = Two glycosyltransferases involved in anthocyanin modi?cation delineated by transcriptome independent component analysis in ''Arabidopsis thaliana'' | journal = The Plant Journal | volume = 69 | issue = 1| pages = 154\u2013167 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-313X.2011.04779.x | pmid = 21899608 | pmc=3507004}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Anthocyanins}}\n\n[[Category:Anthocyanins]]\n[[Category:Flavonoid glucosides]]\n", "text_old": "{{chembox\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 440125119\n| Name = Chrysanthemin\n| ImageFile = Cyanidin 3-O-glucoside.svg\n| ImageSize = 300px\n| IUPACName = <nowiki>(2S,3R,4S,5S,6R)-2-[2-(3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)-5,7-dihydroxychromenylium-3-yl]oxy-6-(hydroxymethyl)oxane-3,4,5-triol chloride</nowiki>\n| OtherNames = Chrysontenin<br>Glucocyanidin<br>Asterin<br>Chrysanthemin<br>Purple corn color<br>Kuromanin<br>Kuromanin chloride<br>Cyanidin 3-glucoside<br>Cyanidol 3-glucoside<br>Cyanidine 3-glucoside<br>Cyanidin 3-O-glucoside<br>cyanidin-3-O-beta-D-glucoside<br>Cyanidin 3-monoglucoside<br>C3G\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 170681\n| InChI = 1/C21H20O11.ClH/c22-7-16-17(27)18(28)19(29)21(32-16)31-15-6-10-12(25)4-9(23)5-14(10)30-20(15)8-1-2-11(24)13(26)3-8;/h1-6,16-19,21-22,27-29H,7H2,(H3-,23,24,25,26);1H/t16-,17-,18+,19-,21-;/m1./s1\n| InChIKey = YTMNONATNXDQJF-UBNZBFALBB\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C21H20O11.ClH/c22-7-16-17(27)18(28)19(29)21(32-16)31-15-6-10-12(25)4-9(23)5-14(10)30-20(15)8-1-2-11(24)13(26)3-8;/h1-6,16-19,21-22,27-29H,7H2,(H3-,23,24,25,26);1H/t16-,17-,18+,19-,21-;/m1./s1\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = YTMNONATNXDQJF-UBNZBFALSA-N\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| CASNo = 7084-24-4\n| PubChem = 197081\n| SMILES = [Cl-].O(c1c([o+]c2c(c1)c(O)cc(O)c2)c3ccc(O)c(O)c3)[C@@H]4O[C@@H]([C@@H](O)[C@H](O)[C@H]4O)CO\n}}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = C<sub>21</sub>H<sub>21</sub>O<sub>11</sub><sup>+</sup>, Cl<sup>\u2212</sup><br>C<sub>21</sub>H<sub>21</sub>ClO<sub>11</sub>\n| MolarMass = 484.83 g/mol (chloride)<br>449.38 g/mol\n| Appearance =\n| Density =\n| MeltingPt =\n| BoilingPt =\n| Solubility =\n  }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards =\n| FlashPt =\n| AutoignitionPt =\n  }}\n}}\n[[File:UV visible spectrum cyanidin3G.PNG|thumb|right|UV visible spectrum of cyanidin 3-O-glucoside.]]\n'''Chrysanthemin''' is an [[anthocyanin]]. It is the 3-[[glucoside]] of [[cyanidin]].\n\n== Natural occurrences ==\nChrysanthemin can be found in the [[Roselle (plant)|roselle plant]] (''Hibiscus sabdariffa'', Malvaceae), different Japanese [[angiosperm]]s,<ref>\"A survey of anthocyanins in sprouting leaves of some Japanese angiosperms studies on anthocyanins, LXV\". Kunijiro Yoshitama, Makiko Ozaku, Michiko Hujii and K\u00f4z\u00f4 Hayashi, ''Journal of plant research'', Volume 85, Number 4, pages 303\u2013306, {{doi|10.1007/BF02490176}}</ref> ''[[Rhaponticum]]'' (Asteraceae),<ref>\"Chrysanthemin and cyanin in species of the genus ''Rhaponticum''. V. V. Vereskovskii and I. I. Chekalinskaya, ''Chemistry of natural compounds'', Volume 14, Number 4, pages 450\u2013451, {{doi|10.1007/BF00565267}}</ref> The fruits of the smooth arrowwood (''[[Viburnum dentatum]]'', Caprifoliaceae) appear blue. One of the major pigments is cyanidin 3-glucoside, but the total mixture is very complex.<ref>\"Food colorants: Anthocyanins\". F. J. Francis and Pericles C. Markakis, ''Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition'', 1989, Volume 28, Issue 4, pages 273\u2013314, {{doi|10.1080/10408398909527503}}</ref>\n\n=== In food ===\nChrysanthemin has been detected in [[blackcurrant]] pomace, in [[Sambucus nigra|European elderberry]],<ref>Foods in which the polyphenol Cyanidin 3-O-glucoside is found, http://www.phenol-explorer.eu/contents/polyphenol/9</ref> in [[Rubus idaeus|red raspberries]], in [[soybean]] [[Seed#Seed coat|seed coats]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Choung|first1=Myoung-Gun|last2=Baek|first2=In-Youl|last3=Kang|first3=Sung-Taeg|last4=Han|first4=Won-Young|last5=Doo-Chull|first5=Shin|last6=Moon|first6=Huhn-Pal|last7=Kang|first7=Kwang-Hee|title=Isolation and Determination of Anthocyanins in Seed Coats of Black Soybean (Glycine max (L.) Merr.)|journal=Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry|date=2001|volume=49|issue=12|pages=5848\u20135851|doi=10.1021/jf010550w|pmid=11743773}}</ref> in [[victoria plum]],<ref>The chemical constituents of victoria plums: Chrysanthemin, acid and pectin contents. D. Dickinson and Joy H. Gawler, ''Journal of the Science of Food and Agriculture'', Volume 7, Issue 11, November 1956, pp. 699\u2013705 {{doi|10.1002/jsfa.2740071103}}</ref> in [[peach]],<ref>Postharvest sensory and phenolic characterization of 'Elegant Lady and 'Carson' peaches. Rodrigo Infante, Loreto Contador, P\u00eda Rubio, Danilo Aros and \u00c1lvaro Pe\u00f1a-Neira, ''Chilean Journal of Agricultural Research'', 71(3), July\u2013September 2011, pages 445\u2013451 ([http://www.scielo.cl/pdf/chiljar/v71n3/at16.pdf article])</ref> [[lychee]] and [[a\u00e7a\u00ed]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Del Pozo-Insfran D, Brenes CH, Talcott ST |title=Phytochemical composition and pigment stability of A\u00e7ai (''Euterpe oleracea'' Mart.) |journal=J. Agric. Food Chem. |volume=52 |issue=6 |pages=1539\u201345 |date=March 2004 |pmid=15030208 |doi=10.1021/jf035189n |url=}}</ref> It is found in [[red orange]]s<ref>Influence of glucose on cyanidin 3-glucoside absorption in rats. Felgines C1, Texier O, Besson C, Vitaglione P, Lamaison JL, Fogliano V, Scalbert A, Vanella L and Galvano F, Mol Nutr Food Res., August 2008, volume 52, issue 8, pages 959-964, {{doi|10.1002/mnfr.200700377}}, {{PMID|18646002}}</ref> and black rice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Um|first=Min Young|last2=Ahn|first2=Jiyun|last3=Ha|first3=Tae Youl|date=2013-09-01|title=Hypolipidaemic effects of cyanidin 3-glucoside rich extract from black rice through regulating hepatic lipogenic enzyme activities|journal=Journal of the Science of Food and Agriculture|volume=93|issue=12|pages=3126\u20133128|doi=10.1002/jsfa.6070|issn=1097-0010|pmid=23471845}}</ref>\n\nIt is the major anthocyanin in [[purple corn]] (''Zea mays''). Purple corn is approved in Japan and listed in the \"[[Existing Food Additive List]]\" as ''purple corn color''.<ref>Anthocyanins isolated from purple corn (''Zea mays'' L.). Hiromitsu Aoki, Noriko Kuze and Yoshiaki Kato ([http://www.ffcr.or.jp/zaidan/ffcrhome.nsf/7bd44c20b0dc562649256502001b65e9/c6698773361b42b249256ba60018e581/$FILE/anthocyanin-FFIJ199.pdf article] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210237/http://www.ffcr.or.jp/zaidan/ffcrhome.nsf/7bd44c20b0dc562649256502001b65e9/c6698773361b42b249256ba60018e581/$FILE/anthocyanin-FFIJ199.pdf |date=2013-10-29 }})</ref>\n\n== Biosynthesis ==\nThe biosynthesis of cyanidin 3-O-glucoside in ''[[Escherichia coli]]'' was demonstrated by means of genetic engineering.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Yan Y, Chemler J, Huang L, Martens S, Koffas MA |title=Metabolic engineering of anthocyanin biosynthesis in ''Escherichia coli'' |journal=Appl. Environ. Microbiol. |volume=71 |issue=7 |pages=3617\u201323 |year=2005 |pmid=16000769 |doi=10.1128/AEM.71.7.3617-3623.2005 |pmc=1169036}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Arabidopsis thaliana]]'', a [[glycosyltransferase]], UGT79B1, is involved in the anthocyanin biosynthetic pathway. UGT79B1 protein converts cyanidin 3-O-glucoside to cyanidin 3-O-xylosyl(1\u21922)glucoside.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Yonekura-Sakakibara | first1 = Keiko | last2 = Fukushima | first2 = Atsushi | last3 = Nakabayashi | first3 = Ryo | last4 = Hanada | first4 = Kousuke | last5 = Matsuda | first5 = Fumio | last6 = Sugawara | first6 = Satoko | last7 = Inoue | first7 = Eri | last8 = Kuromori | first8 = Takashi | last9 = Ito | first9 = Takuya | last10 = Shinozaki | first10 = Kazuo | last11 = Wangwattana | first11 = Bunyapa | last12 = Yamazaki | first12 = Mami | year = 2012 | title = Two glycosyltransferases involved in anthocyanin modi?cation delineated by transcriptome independent component analysis in ''Arabidopsis thaliana'' | journal = The Plant Journal | volume = 69 | issue = 1| pages = 154\u2013167 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-313X.2011.04779.x | pmid = 21899608 | pmc=3507004}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Anthocyanins}}\n\n[[Category:Anthocyanins]]\n[[Category:Flavonoid glucosides]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chrysanthemin"}
